928. Ex animo. The phrase miser ex animo is not uncommon (Trz'u. 398, Epid. 526, Stich. 2). Some editors put the comma not after auimo, but after eura, which necessitates omission of the second et. With the combination ex auimo et cura may be compared Cist. 60 Doleo ab animo, doleo ab oeulis, doleo ab aem-[tudine. (Strictly speaking eat in the phrase ex auimo has not quite the same force as in the phrase ex eura, ‘owing to anxiety’3 cf. Poeu. prol. 69 Coozz'oitur ipse iu morbum ex aegritudine, Cas. 361 adsudascis iam ex metu 3 see note on v. 959 below.) Seyffert proposes me sat et, pointing out that satis has been substituted for sat in our MSS. at Aul. 187, Pers. 839. Here however satis is established by the consensus of A and P. Dolui. In Plautus' plays we can trace the gradual development of doleo from an Impersonal to a Persona] Verb. The normal expression is dolet mihi or id (hoe) dolet mihi (cf. v, 152): often the subject is some part of the body, e.g. oculi dolent Men. 882, renes dolent Curc. 236, hirae dolent Cure. 2383 cf. animus mila· dolet Mero. 388. But there are not wanting examples of the persona] use.
